<DOC><DOCNO> AP900721-0005 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-90 0155EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-North-Chronology     07-21 0882</FIRST><SECOND>PM-North-Chronology,0915</SECOND><HEAD>With PM-North, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here is a chronology of key events in theOliver North Iran-Contra case:   1988andequals;   March 16 _ North, former Reagan National Security Adviser JohnM. Poindexter, former Maj. Gen. Richard Secord and Iranian-Americanbusinessman Albert Hakim are indicted.   March 18 _ North announces his retirement from the Marine Corps,says he may subpoena ``the highest ranking officials in ourgovernment.''   June 6 _ U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell orders separatetrials for the four defendants. Independent Counsel Lawrence E.Walsh says the next day that North will go first.   Nov. 7 _ One of 16 criminal counts against North, fabricating adocument, is dismissed.   Nov. 21 _ Gesell says that if North stands trial, the court willhave little control over the testimony of witnesses ``acquaintedwith high security matters.'' He appeals to President Reagan todecide whether the government will allow the trial to take place.   Nov. 29 _ Another count against North is dismissed: wire fraud.   Dec. 1 _ Reagan rules out a North pardon but says ``dutyrequires'' his administration to block release of secret documentsNorth wants for his trial.   Dec. 12 _ Gesell tells North he can't use 3,500 secret documentsbut can use more than 300, roughly the same number planned to beintroduced by the prosecution. The decision removes a majorobstacle to the trial going forward.   Dec. 30 _ North subpoenas Reagan and President-elect Bush asdefense witnesses. Gesell, after Bush is sworn as president thefollowing month, rules he won't be called.   1989andequals;   Jan. 5 _ Prosecutors ask Gesell to dismiss conspiracy and theftcharges, citing North's ``insistence on introducing classifiedinformation in his defense'' and the Reagan administration'srefusal to release material the judge ruled North would need.Gesell later dismisses those counts.   Twelve felony counts remain, including lying to Congress in 1985and 1986 about his efforts on behalf of the Contras and lying tothe attorney general about the National Security Council's role indiverting money from the Iran arms sales.   North also is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800 securitysystem at his home from co-defendant Secord, converting to his ownuse at least $4,300 in traveler's checks from Contra leader AdolfoCalero, and conspiring to defraud the government of tax revenue byusing a tax-exempt foundation to funnel money to the Contras.   Jan. 31 _ Jury selection begins.   Feb. 21 _ The trial opens with prosecutor John Keker portrayingNorth as a liar who ``places himself above the law.'' Defenselawyer Brendan Sullivan calls North a patriotic Marine who obeyedthe orders of his commander-in-chief.   March 21 _ Security consultant Glenn Robinette testifies thatNorth let Secord pay for a security fence at his home and thentried to cover up the deal after he left the White House.   March 23 _ Fawn Hall, North's secretary at the White House,tearfully testifies that he was a tireless and selfless boss andtheir shredding of Iran-Contra documents ``was no big deal.''   March 28 _ Former Attorney General Edwin Meese III testifiesadministration officials were worried about impeachment of Reaganafter they discovered the Iran-Contra link.   March 31 _ Gesell rejects North's request that he order Reaganto testify, saying there is no proof the former presidentauthorized North to commit crimes.   April 6 _ North takes the stand, saying he was merely a Marinefollowing White House orders.   April 7 _ North concedes he lied to the House IntelligenceCommittee at an Aug. 6, 1986, meeting at the White House at whichhe denied providing assistance to the Contras.   April 12 _ North testifies he thought he was protecting Reaganwhen he altered Iran-Contra memos before investigators from theJustice Department could get a look at them.   April 18 _ Prosecutor Keker, in a hard-hitting summation, says,``North and McFarlane were following Adolf Hitler's old strategy,which is the victor will never be asked if he told the truth.''   April 19 _ In an emotional closing argument, Sullivan says Northbecame a ``sacrificial lamb'' in the Reagan White House and wasfired to spare the former president political harm.   May 4 _ North is convicted of falsifying and destroyingdocuments, accepting an illegal gratuity and aiding and abetting inthe obstruction of Congress. He was acquitted of five other countsof lying to or obstructing Congress, of lying to Meese, ofillegally converting traveler's checks to his own use and ofconspiring to defraud the IRS.   June 30 _ Gesell denies a mistrial motion filed by the defenseon grounds that juror Tara Leigh King had falsely denied in aquestionnaire that she or her relatives had ever been involved in acourt proceeding or criminal investigation.   July 5 _ Gesell sentences North to a suspended prison term and a$150,000 fine for his role in the Iran-Contra affair. North isplaced on two years' probation and ordered to perform 1,200 hoursof community service administering a new program to help inner-cityyouth avoid involvement in drugs.   1990andequals;   July 20, 1990 _ A federal appeals court sets aside North'sconvictions, reversing the one on destroying documents and orderinga hearing to see whether all three were impermissibly tainted bycongressional testimony that he gave under a grant of immunity.</TEXT></DOC>